    <div class="content">

				<span class="paragraph-0">
					<p>Thereâ€™s something about hot chocolate that soothes the psyche.</p>
				</span>
				<span class="paragraph-1">
					<p>Add some creamy milk and a sprinkling of marshmallows and â€” <em>voila</em> â€” you have the perfect drink to warm body and soul on cold, January days when the world seems so wintry.</p>
				</span>
                <p>While hot chocolate and hot cocoa arenâ€™t the same â€” cocoa is made from a powder extracted from cocoa beans but missing the cocoa butter that gives chocolate its richness â€” theyâ€™re both satisfying, especially when sipped from steamy mugs that defrost fingers frozen by sledding or shoveling snow.</p>
            
                <p>Hot chocolate has been a drink of choice as far back as 1500 BC, according to <a href="http://whatscookingamerica.net">whatscookingamerica.net</a>. Thatâ€™s when the Americasâ€™ first inhabitants, the Olmecs, began soaking the seeds of the cocoa plant and drinking the flavored water that resulted. Soon the Mayans started sipping the beverage, then traded the valued beans to the Aztecs.</p>
            
                <p>Christopher Columbus was the first European to taste a chocolate drink, on his fourth visit to the Americas, and brought the beans back to Spain. But it wasnâ€™t until the conquistador Hernando Cortez reported that Mexican Emperor Montezuma drank chocolate out of a golden goblet that it caught on in the Spanish court. The Spanish added sugar to sweeten the drink that Montezuma reportedly used as an aphrodisiac.</p>
            
                <p>It was the English who added milk and turned hot chocolate into a trendy after-dinner drink in the 1700s. Like colonial-era Starbucks, â€œchocolate houses,â€ became as popular as coffee shops are today, sccording to the website.</p>
            
                <p>Hot chocolate and cocoa consumption increase in the fall and winter, both chocolate producers Hersheyâ€™s and ConAgra Foods â€” maker of Swiss Miss cocoa mixes â€” report.</p>
            
                <p>ConAgra said it sells enough Swiss Miss to make approximately 1 billion cups a year.</p>
            
                <p>Swiss Miss cocoa packets come in a variety of styles, some with marshmallows already included.</p>
            
                <p>â€œMost people buy milk chocolate. Marshmallow is number two. Some folks like to add their own marshmallows, and the most passionate about marshmallows sometimes buy our Marshmallow Madness item with five times more marshmallows,â€ said Lanie Friedman, a spokeswoman for ConAgra Foods.</p>
            
                <p>Hersheyâ€™s suggests that other toppings â€” like Reeseâ€™s Peanut Butter Cups â€” or flavored extracts such as almond or orange can add variety to your chocolate drink.</p>
            
                <p>At the Bittersweet Cafe in the Moorestown Mall, Irwin Solon said he only uses quality ingredients that promote health. The cafeâ€™s hot chocolate and hot cocoa are â€œhydrogenated oil and trans-fat free,â€ he said. His wife, Nitza Solon, owns the cafe, and since sheâ€™s a breast cancer survivor, the cafe serves only foods that the couple found to be healthful, including soups, sandwiches, pastries and smoothies, which are made from real fruit.</p>
            
                <p>The business also sponsors a book swap. Customers donate books; other customers can buy the books for a donation of $1 or more, to fund cancer research.</p>
            
                <p>â€œWeâ€™ve collected quite a lot,â€ Solen said.</p>
            
                <p>The cafe serves four types of hot chocolate supplied by Dr. Smoothie, a California firm that says its hot chocolate is free of hydrogenated oil and trans fats. They include Belgium dark cocoa and Chocolate Truffle cocoa made Swiss-style with milk, a Mexican spiced cocoa and â€œChocoholics Choice,â€ an American-style drink of pure hot chocolate, which features milk steamed to add froth and a dollop of whipped cream on top.</p>
            
                <p>The cafeâ€™s barista, Jayne Wenstrom, said itâ€™s best to dissolve the hot chocolate or cocoa powder in a little hot water before adding milk. The milk used in the store is steamed to make it frothy, but if you donâ€™t have a frother at home, boil the milk, Solden said, but only long enough to get it really hot. Whole milk will make the richest brew, but skim and 2 percent milk work well too.</p>
            
                <p>Add the hot milk to the mix, then top it off with marshmallows or whipped cream.</p>
            
                <p>Linda Stahl, director of Hersheyâ€™s Kitchens, offered the following tips to ensure a great-tasting cup of hot chocolate at home:</p>
            
                <p>Use whole milk for a really creamy drink.</p>
            
                <p>Top with whipped cream and a sprinkle of cocoa.</p>
            
                <p>Stir the drink often so the cocoa solids settle out.</p>
            
                <p>Serve with marshmallows (Marshmallows dipped in chocolate are especially nice.)</p>
            
                <p>Make variations by adding Â½ teaspoon different flavored extracts (almond, orange, mint, maple) to each cup of cocoa.</p>
            
                <p>Serve with cookies for a snack.</p>
            
    
